WEBVTT

00:01.415 --> 00:04.358
Angela Caso, C-A-S-S-O. C-A-S-S-O. Apparently 
it sounds like an Italian name, but it seems like

00:07.963 --> 00:17.354
generations back it was spelled C-A-Z-O. Why and 
who changed it, we don't know. But now the whole

00:21.639 --> 00:24.983
family is C-A-S-S-O. And I was born in Revolaredo. 
So was my sister. So was my mother. And my father was

00:34.171 --> 00:37.075
born in the state of Coahuila. But they moved. I 
really don't know how young he was when they moved

00:39.098 --> 00:43.684
to Nuevo Laredo. And he and my mother were married 
when she was only 16 years old. She was just a child,

00:51.293 --> 00:54.337
so to speak. And there were only two of us, my 
sister, who is four years older than myself, and I.

01:00.578 --> 01:04.762
Unfortunately, we lost mother when I was just a 
very, very young baby. And even though my father

01:05.783 --> 01:15.473
was very young, he did not remarry until after we 
were married and after I had children. So, as a

01:15.493 --> 01:27.766
consequence, he moved in, or rather, my 
grandmother, my father's mother, was a widow. And

01:27.786 --> 01:29.067
she had to... daughters and married daughters, 
and one of his sisters, his oldest sister, was the

01:29.620 --> 01:45.876
one who raised me, who raised us, but I think of her 
just like my mother because she actually took care

01:29.620 --> 01:45.876
of me since I was five months old. I don't stop to 
realize that I'm sure my grandmother had a lot to do

01:46.637 --> 01:49.960
with it. Was your grandmother living with you too? 
Yes, in other words, my father, when mother died,

01:58.358 --> 02:00.440
my father moved in with his family. Or rather, he 
made a home for his family. He was always

02:04.825 --> 02:12.213
supporting my widowed grandmother and his two 
sisters, young sisters. And so from there on, of

02:13.334 --> 02:21.042
course, there were different moves because my 
father was a customs man. He worked for customs. He

02:22.543 --> 02:26.087
had an important position. And we lived for a 
while, we lived in what is now, well, in Piedras

02:26.894 --> 02:33.825
Negras. In those days it was called Porfirio Diaz. 
Yes, this was before 1910. Yes. But I don't

02:41.196 --> 02:48.167
remember except that my mother, the one who raised 
me, married at the time. In Piedras Negras. in what

02:51.565 --> 03:19.986
did she marry in oh wow she married a man from this 
side from from the northern side so uh my father in

02:51.565 --> 03:19.986
the meantime had been transferred to piedras 
negras and he took his family my grandmother his

02:51.565 --> 03:19.986
two sisters my sister and myself but that night i 
started crying and crying and crying i wanted mama

02:51.565 --> 03:19.986
i wanted mom so um he wired because i guess in those 
days wiring a sending telegram was Are you

03:20.270 --> 03:23.394
comfortable there, Miss Catherine? Would you 
like to sit on one of these rockers? You try.

03:30.883 --> 03:34.047
It's part of the family's old furniture, too. So 
anyway, my mother and her husband moved to Piedras

03:35.089 --> 03:41.998
Negras because of me. But that's when the 
revolution started, as far as I really don't know.

03:47.304 --> 03:49.467
How old were you when it began? But let's see, I 
guess I was three years old. Then we moved back to

03:55.820 --> 03:58.283
Nuevo Laredo. When, I don't know. I really don't 
know.

04:03.751 --> 04:12.923
About our moving to this side when we actually 
became refugees, I remember some, just vaguely, I

04:13.291 --> 04:17.978
do remember, we lived right in the heart of what is 
now Nueva Laredo. Have you been across? Have you

04:19.900 --> 04:20.822
been to Mexico? All right. The first little plaza, 
let's see, one, two blocks west. That was where our

04:29.754 --> 04:31.196
home was. And I don't remember, it's funny, but I 
just don't remember what the house was like. I know

04:39.008 --> 04:40.350
it was a brick house. I don't remember what 
furniture was in it. I don't remember anything

04:43.416 --> 04:47.002
except one thing, this picture. That's the only 
thing that I remember of my early, early childhood

04:48.745 --> 04:54.976
days. It's a beautiful picture. It's a beautiful 
picture, and it was a picture on her namesake. She

05:02.228 --> 05:09.416
was my father's youngest sister, and she died when 
she was 90 years old, so he named me after her. And I

05:09.476 --> 05:14.082
remember that- Angelina. Angela. Angela. 
A-N-G-L-A, Angela. And of course, she was Angela

05:16.424 --> 05:22.151
Caso, C-A-S-S-O, the same as my name, my maiden 
name. So anyway, that's the only thing that I

05:22.892 --> 05:27.998
remember, that, and I always had a dog. What kind of 
dog? Just a plain old dog. Just any dog. As long as it

05:35.436 --> 05:36.578
was a dog. Ordinary dog. Ordinary dog would do for 
me. And of course my dolls and things like that. And

05:42.925 --> 05:51.256
my father was a very, very, he was not with the 
revolutionists at all. He belonged to the old

05:53.832 --> 05:55.234
party, so to speak. He had been a government 
employee with customs under the administration.

05:59.719 --> 06:03.263
I mean, he was still, he was a porfirista all the 
time. In fact, they used to say that when they asked

06:04.184 --> 06:10.652
me as a young child, no, I would make this question. 
It's very, very childish, but I would always ask

06:11.673 --> 06:19.923
the questions, what are you? Carrancista or 
porfirista? No. Maderista or Porfirista?

06:25.083 --> 06:27.205
Because there was Madero and there was Porfirio.

06:29.948 --> 06:31.470
Católica o protestante? Catholic or Protestant? 
It seemed like they, as far as I was concerned, they

06:33.572 --> 06:39.139
had to be Catholics. Rich or poor? And we weren't 
rich. We were Catholics, yes, but we weren't rich.

06:48.676 --> 06:52.861
But yet I wanted those three qualities. Just like a 
child, I guess. So anyway, I never attended school

06:54.943 --> 06:58.267
in Mexico. Do you remember what year your family 
moved across the border? Sister says that we moved

07:03.753 --> 07:05.916
in 1912. In 1912. So this would have been after Diaz 
was overthrown and Madero had become president.

07:15.046 --> 07:16.928
Yes, but I think that it was The revolution was 
between Huerta. And the Carrancistas. And the

07:22.169 --> 07:23.211
Carrancistas. And Huerta, of course, by that time 
represented the federal government again. Yes,

07:28.339 --> 07:29.260
yes. So my aunt, the one who raised me, lived on this 
side. I remember that many times, I couldn't tell

07:35.750 --> 07:45.885
you how many times, but I do remember that during 
the night they would wake us up and we would have to

07:46.523 --> 07:53.069
walk across because there was the alarm that the 
Revolucionistas were coming. So half asleep and

07:53.089 --> 07:58.674
just they practically dragged us. Of course as I 
say it was right in town and we didn't have a car and

07:58.714 --> 08:07.082
very few people did. So we would cross the bridge 
and get to Mother's. She lived where Crestor is now

08:14.806 --> 08:18.810
located, which is in the very heart of town. And of 
course, we would come and stay with her. Then it

08:22.774 --> 08:24.175
would quiet down. My father would say, all right, 
everything is all right. It was just a false alarm,

08:27.198 --> 08:30.481
so we would get back across. How many times we did 
that, I don't know. But when the real thing

08:36.907 --> 08:42.993
happened, we had already crossed. My 
grandmother. one of my aunts, my sister, and

08:46.244 --> 08:49.547
myself. My father didn't come with us because he 
joined the federal government. And he was... He

08:57.155 --> 08:58.617
joined the military? Well, in other words, I guess 
he wanted to help. And he had been sent the

09:03.562 --> 09:09.528
paycheck, the payroll, for all of the custom men. 
And he felt like he had to find them and pay each one

09:10.349 --> 09:16.015
what was due to him. And so we came, and I do remember 
that my grandmother used to cry quite often

09:16.248 --> 09:25.100
because she hadn't heard from Daddy, of course. I 
wasn't aware of the fact that Daddy was in danger.

09:32.089 --> 09:46.187
Then there's another very,

09:32.089 --> 09:46.187
how shall I put it, very much alive thing

09:32.089 --> 09:46.187
in my mind. And that was when they burned Nuevo 
Laredes. They set fire to Nuevo Laredes. And we

09:52.827 --> 09:59.177
could see the flames and the smoke and everything. 
And my grandmother was crying. She says, there

10:01.721 --> 10:03.063
goes my home. And of course, I mean, I guess they say 
that my grandmother was just thinking that it was

10:03.765 --> 10:10.876
her home. It did go down in fire. I mean, it was 
destroyed. As most of the city was. It was not a big

10:15.929 --> 10:18.772
city, but anyway, everything. And the only thing, 
I don't believe that we brought any clothes with

10:18.832 --> 10:23.597
us. I really don't believe we did. The only thing 
that my grandmother made sure that was crossed at

10:25.539 --> 10:31.785
the very first time was this picture. She brought 
it and left it here for safekeeping. So you had left

10:39.442 --> 10:44.431
and come over here, but you hadn't brought that 
much with you. Perhaps they were planning to go

10:44.771 --> 10:46.655
back? Yes, I'm sure that my father was very 
optimistic. He couldn't believe that the

10:51.002 --> 10:59.577
government would be...

11:00.890 --> 11:03.053
output by the revolution. I don't think anyone 
ever believed it was going to last so long. He

11:05.757 --> 11:11.985
didn't believe, he didn't want to accept the fact 
that unfortunately that was what was happening.

11:12.246 --> 11:15.069
Unfortunately for them, but fortunately for many 
others. So I don't know how many hours or how many

11:17.212 --> 11:24.082
what the fire lasted. I couldn't tell you because 
I'm sure that it was extinguished to the best of

11:24.102 --> 11:30.070
their abilities. whichever way they were able to 
do it. But I remember that after it was all over,

11:35.433 --> 11:41.261
crossing the bridge was no problem. It was just 
like going down the street. There was no

11:43.785 --> 11:47.710
immigration department to ask you where you were 
born. There was no registration at all on either

11:47.730 --> 11:50.054
side? Nothing whatsoever. And my grandmother 
went across the river and she came back and she said

11:52.457 --> 12:01.069
that she had, as a young, Her family was a family of 
means.

12:09.629 --> 12:26.871
My great-grandfather was a wealthy man, and his 
children naturally, in those days, they thought

12:09.629 --> 12:26.871
that the boys were the ones who were supposed to 
keep most everything, not the girls. But she did

12:27.087 --> 12:30.351
have some things like silver pieces. She didn't 
bring any of them. And they were all lost in the

12:32.034 --> 12:33.456
family? They were all lost. The only thing she 
found was all the silver melted. But of course

12:39.744 --> 12:46.934
there was a lot of

12:39.744 --> 12:46.934
robbery around. I mean, it was in the hands of... In 
fact, I don't even know who was responsible. They

12:55.059 --> 13:09.362
even say, my husband, if you would ask my husband, 
he would say that it was the same general who was

12:55.059 --> 13:09.362
with the government that set fire to the Nuevo 
Laredo rather than have it fall in the hands of

13:09.612 --> 13:13.697
the... Carencistas. Yes. But of course, I mean, it 
would be very hard to prove anything like that. Why

13:20.285 --> 13:21.687
would your husband say that? Because he believed 
in the revolution. And you say his family is not...

13:26.112 --> 13:29.716
No, they're not refugees. They've been here for a 
long time. Well, his family was from the little

13:31.599 --> 13:36.425
town of Guerrero. Yes. And his grandfather... 
More or less around that time, I believe, that was

13:40.409 --> 13:44.134
when my husband lost his father. And his mother, 
with all her children, moved to Zapata, to a ranch

13:44.755 --> 13:53.046
that my husband's grandfather had. And his family 
name is Zapata. Yes. Is he a descendant of the

13:56.150 --> 13:58.613
Antonio Zapata? No, no. Not to my knowledge. I 
really don't know. He always makes a joke of it, and

14:02.238 --> 14:07.986
he says that he comes from...

14:09.468 --> 14:16.715
Zapata, the revolutionist Emiliano Zapata. 
That's a long way off. He makes a big joke out of it. I

14:22.461 --> 14:31.490
don't believe that he really knows whether, he 
says that there was some relation with Antonio

14:22.461 --> 14:31.490
Zapata. Yes. And the problem was because the name 
Zapata is not a very common name. And so after that,

14:39.033 --> 14:42.876
we stayed here. And I remember that when my father 
came back, of course my grandmother was elated

14:43.677 --> 14:51.765
over the fact that her son was back home. But there 
was no working here. I mean, we were left

14:56.569 --> 15:00.653
absolutely penniless. And we couldn't stay with 
mother because her home was big. An average size

15:09.020 --> 15:13.826
home for a couple, but not for four more people. 
Let's say four more people. Because it was my

15:16.470 --> 15:20.114
father, my grandmother, and five. My aunt, my 
sister, and myself. So we moved. I can't even

15:25.641 --> 15:27.163
remember where. Houses were very, very hard to 
find. At first we lived in a small, small place that

15:31.909 --> 15:37.997
I can't even tell you. The only thing that I 
remember is that my father said, you girls cannot

15:38.365 --> 15:46.233
go out and play with anyone here in this 
neighborhood. Because I guess he felt like they

15:46.273 --> 15:52.579
were not our class, our kind. But we grabbed 
whatever we could. And surviving was actually the

15:55.642 --> 16:02.328
main thing. And many other people, like the 
Longorias, came, you know, . I've heard the name.

16:13.554 --> 16:14.014
All right. They came and moved in with my aunt, who 
lives at a corner from us. Because they, too,

16:20.560 --> 16:24.844
didn't have a house in which they were to move to. 
Well, Loretta was really full of refugees at that

16:25.064 --> 16:27.446
time. Yes, that was the trouble. See, so you 
grabbed whatever you could. Then we moved to

16:31.810 --> 16:35.273
another house, and it was half of the house. We 
lived in half of the house, the other half of the

16:35.313 --> 16:37.515
house. a friend of my daddy's read, he and his wife. 
And it was like that for several years until we were

16:42.105 --> 16:57.483
able to, daddy was able to get back on his own two 
feet and we started school and that's about it.

16:58.184 --> 17:00.967
Well what kind of work did your father eventually 
find? Well at first he did anything. I really don't

17:04.040 --> 17:07.885
know what he did, but he would do just anything. But 
finally, that's when custom brokers started. My

17:14.113 --> 17:20.181
husband is a custom broker, a forwarding agent. 
That's what they're called now. But we used to call

17:21.442 --> 17:25.307
them custom brokers, agente aduanal. And my 
father worked with an agente aduanal. He ran the

17:29.504 --> 17:32.248
office for Mr. Gonzalez. And, of course, it was in 
his line of work because he had always been a custom

17:32.929 --> 17:36.954
man. Had he spoken English before the Revolution? 
No, he didn't speak a word of English. Not a word. He

17:42.622 --> 17:44.064
never knew any English. He never did learn. I never 
heard a word of English in my home. Never. Not a

17:47.949 --> 17:48.490
word.

17:51.534 --> 17:54.938
So that made it even more difficult for him on this 
side. Of course, Spanish here was the main

17:54.958 --> 17:57.722
language.

18:01.212 --> 18:30.612
you would go to the stores and everybody knew what 
you were talking about so it wasn't as much of a

18:01.212 --> 18:30.612
handicap as it would have been someplace else now 
knowing English or vice versa knowing Spanish is a

18:01.212 --> 18:30.612
must we live in a bilingual absolutely bilingual 
Laredo is almost completely on both sides

18:01.212 --> 18:30.612
bilingual community it is a bilingual community 
really And I don't remember of any, absolutely, I

18:31.452 --> 18:39.688
absolutely don't remember of any...

18:43.375 --> 18:52.313
When I started school, I don't remember that I 
was...

18:53.137 --> 18:58.564
The fact that I came from Mexico or that I was 
Mexican had anything to do with it. Of course, most

18:58.664 --> 19:09.277
of my classmates were Mexican, of Mexican 
descent, maybe Americans, because we keep on

18:58.664 --> 19:09.277
thinking of Mexicans when we are really American. 
I am an American in that I became an American

19:09.598 --> 19:13.022
citizen. My husband still is a Mexican citizen. He 
is. Yes. And when my grandmother passed away, She

19:22.381 --> 19:23.845
was buried in Mexico. When my father passed away, 
he was buried in Mexico. My uncle passed away and

19:29.081 --> 19:31.788
his wife passed away. They were buried in Mexico. 
So they retained very strong emotional ties. They

19:36.790 --> 19:39.152
were very, very strongly tied to. And we still are. 
We are. Why did your father not return to Mexico

19:41.315 --> 19:44.899
after the revolution? Because he was not allowed 
to go. Well, things quieted down. Yes, they

19:50.585 --> 19:52.207
quieted down. But he was absolutely against 
everything that the revolutionists stood for.

20:01.718 --> 20:03.340
And they, naturally, they would have In the first 
place, he didn't want to go as long as it was in the

20:03.775 --> 20:11.951
hand of the new party. And in the second place, 
there was a danger of his being imprisoned. He was

20:18.063 --> 20:20.548
still identified with the idea. Yes. He was still 
identified, and not only that, he was still

20:21.309 --> 20:24.636
helping. Yeah, Felix Diaz was still in Mexico, or 
off and on, up until 1919 or later, wasn't he? I

20:35.031 --> 20:36.613
believe he was. There was always the possibility 
of Diaz countering. Well, Felix was the nephew.

20:43.100 --> 20:45.282
Yes, those were my father's dreams. And I remember 
that he used to cry, literally cry. You could see

20:49.386 --> 20:55.112
his tears rolling down his cheeks when he stood and 
looked across. into his country, or he would hear

20:55.632 --> 21:04.222
the bugles, because Laredo was a very quiet town. 
So if the soldiers were, if for any reason you could

21:04.923 --> 21:13.333
hear the bugles, he would cry. He longed to be in 
Mexico. I don't remember, I don't know what year it

21:16.336 --> 21:20.541
was that he went back. But we never returned. We 
stayed here. Because there was actually, there

21:25.687 --> 21:29.092
wasn't anything for him to do in Mexico. What year 
did he die? Daddy died in 1952. In 1952. The first

21:34.600 --> 21:40.009
year that I know, I remember in September of 1952. 
So I remember that our oldest son had been, that was

21:40.409 --> 21:47.199
his first year in college when Daddy died. He had 
just gone off to Missouri to Kemper Military

