27:59.415 --> 28:03.862
And my father was very much against it, but it was 
her own home. Just the land, naturally, because

28:05.664 --> 28:11.753
the house was destroyed.

28:12.121 --> 28:19.361
Right now it's very, very valuable, but it was her 
desire and there wasn't anything we could do. This

28:19.401 --> 28:21.828
is not infrequent.

28:24.095 --> 28:27.143
There's a very interesting story about from some 
towns I studied that were disrupted by Paricutin

28:27.275 --> 28:31.984
volcano. Yes. And they moved and they sold. Yeah. 
And one man, he didn't even sell his land. Of

28:38.095 --> 28:40.319
course, volcanic ash had fallen on it. And it 
wasn't worth anything then. But it's very good

28:42.784 --> 28:43.845
now. What he did was tear his papers up. He just tore 
them up and burned them and said, no more town, no

28:48.031 --> 28:53.496
more land, and left. And they say he still cries 
about it. He lives in California now. He sits down.

29:00.724 --> 29:03.286
Crying won't bring it back, though. Not even 
selling it. But this is not uncommon, apparently.

29:07.771 --> 29:12.456
It's just a reaction to catastrophe, really. I 
guess so. I'll remember that, just in case. But

29:18.360 --> 29:23.807
now, your mother's, or your father's family from 
Coahuila, what town were they from? Candela.

29:24.848 --> 29:25.569
Candela. Yes. Were they ranchers or ? Yes, yes, and 
ranchers. So I remember that my grandmother used

29:31.156 --> 29:43.030
to say that when they would travel from one, from 
Candela to some other place, she had many sisters,

29:31.156 --> 29:43.030
and they would all wear sort of like porcelain that 
were made for that purpose with wide strips. And

29:54.361 --> 29:56.343
those were filled with the gold coins. Because I 
imagine they feared being attacked.

30:04.992 --> 30:07.674
They raised a lot of sheep and goats. And when my 
great grandfather would sail, I guess, I don't

30:12.811 --> 30:19.699
know, I remember that one thing that my 
grandmother used to tell us. Her name was Barreda.

30:24.425 --> 30:26.727
B-A-R-R-E-D-A. And she said, she used to tell us 
that actually her name was De La Barreda. De La

30:33.535 --> 30:34.496
Barreda. And there were two brothers who were 
given Well royalties from Spain, one was his name

30:43.085 --> 30:57.349
was Ramon and the other one was Fructuoso and this 
Ramon was my great great grandfather. Did he come

30:58.270 --> 30:59.993
directly from Spain? Yes, directly from Spain and 
Fructuoso was lost. They don't know whether the

31:06.644 --> 31:08.788
Indians caught him or what. They never did hear 
from him anymore. So the only branch of the La

31:12.772 --> 31:19.418
Barredas was from this Ramon de la Barreda. But 
then they dropped the De La and just called

31:19.438 --> 31:22.982
themselves Barreda. It seems like I read 
somewhere that a lot of families dropped the De La

31:23.483 --> 31:31.671
during the war for Mexican independence or 
shortly afterwards. Well, I imagine it could have

31:31.691 --> 31:36.316
been then that they did it. But there were rich 
people. And my grandfather, Picasso, came from a

31:38.982 --> 31:45.090
small town, Ahualewas. Ahualewas is in the state 
of Nuevo León. Now how did he, oh wait a minute,

31:52.359 --> 31:57.786
that's your father, how did he meet your mother? My 
father, or you're talking about my grandfather,

32:01.823 --> 32:05.247
My grandfather was from Ahualewas. Oh, your 
grandfather. How did he meet your grandmother?

32:08.570 --> 32:09.911
Oh, that I don't know. She never told you that? I 
wish she would have told me. I wish. She would have

32:13.395 --> 32:14.256
been interested. And the only aunt we had living, 
who had a tremendous memory, my daddy's older

32:14.276 --> 32:29.772
sister, older than himself, she remembered, she 
knew everything, but we never took We never

32:30.190 --> 32:35.116
stopped to ask her those little things that mean so 
much in life. In fact, she gave me this set. It was

32:38.300 --> 32:43.607
hers, and she told me, you keep it, you take it. And 
so I treasure it most highly, and I treasure that

32:43.627 --> 32:47.933
picture, too. Because that picture, to me, is part 
of my childhood. Wherever I went, the first thing

32:51.898 --> 32:58.847
that my grandmother would sit doing was that the 
picture was hung in a place where it's very heavy,

32:59.283 --> 33:05.551
where it wouldn't break or fall or something. Did 
your aunt also come to the United States, your

33:06.953 --> 33:10.598
father's older sister? Yes. The one I'm talking 
about? No, no. She lived in Nuevo Laredo. Her

33:18.008 --> 33:19.870
husband also came from Candela. And they came, I 
imagine, during the revolution, they came to

33:21.212 --> 33:27.440
Nuevo Laredo. I really don't know when. And they 
only had one daughter, and she still lives. She's

33:34.592 --> 33:40.918
still living, and she has a nice home on Aveo 
Avenue, but she lives by herself. And she's a very

33:41.639 --> 33:43.181
strange person. I mean, she's had a hard life in 
that she's by herself. Economically, she doesn't

33:48.946 --> 33:52.249
like anything. But she lives a very, very sad life, 
and no matter We asked her to come over and spend

33:59.628 --> 34:02.856
some days with us. Oh no, she would never think of 
leaving her home. And so as a result, her life is

34:06.565 --> 34:11.237
rather sad. She reads a lot. And she's up to 
everything. But her mother had a tremendous

34:16.827 --> 34:20.632
memory, I'm telling you. This is actually your 
grandmother's sister you're talking about. No,

34:23.656 --> 34:25.859
I'm talking about my father's sister. Your 
father's sister. His oldest sister. I didn't know

34:27.862 --> 34:30.305
any of my grandmother's sisters. None of them. 
This is your father's oldest sister. I did know my

34:33.169 --> 34:37.375
grandmother's brother, Ramon. Named after his 
father, Ramon de la Valeria.

34:45.595 --> 34:50.965
lived in Monterey, at least his daughters still 
live in Monterey. So, and then on my mother's side,

34:53.188 --> 35:04.228
my grandfather also worked, he was a custom man 
also, and his name was Barrera.

35:06.959 --> 35:09.563
B-A-R-R-E-R-A. Well, that's very similar. Very 
similar, except for the D. So I'm Caso on my

35:11.285 --> 35:17.673
father's side, Barrera on my mother's side. And 
then Barrera, my third name, and then Martinez.

35:24.883 --> 35:28.788
Now, after you came here, you went to school. Oh, 
yes. How long did you go to school? Well, I

35:31.792 --> 35:36.679
graduated from high school, and then... I started 
teaching without, with nothing but a teacher's

35:37.216 --> 35:50.171
certificate that you were able to obtain by taking 
a Jillian. I went to summer school in San Marcos and

35:50.391 --> 35:59.542
I took what was required in order to obtain a 
teaching certificate. And we took exams. every

36:02.225 --> 36:07.232
single course that we had taken during our 12 years 
of school. Everything, just everything. And I got

36:11.177 --> 36:13.961
my certificate, and I felt like I was safe. I came 
home with my certificate, ready to teach. A

36:20.910 --> 36:25.517
requirement to teach was you had to be an American 
citizen. My father said no.

36:30.490 --> 36:35.857
You are a Mexican, and I want you to remain a 
Mexican. But later on, he came in without my

36:37.239 --> 36:59.991
really, I didn't exactly beg him, but I guess I must 
have made him realize that it was a shame that I

36:37.239 --> 36:59.991
could help, and yet I was unable to because of his 
pride to remain always a Mexican citizen. We lived

37:00.173 --> 37:00.994
here. This was a country that had given us a home.

37:08.646 --> 37:15.857
So when I got my citizenship papers, I started 
teaching, as I told you. And I taught for just for 30

37:15.877 --> 37:19.802
years. For 30 years? Just 30 years? Just 30 years. 
But in the meantime, of course, I couldn't keep on

37:22.887 --> 37:27.514
teaching with that little old certificate. they 
offered extension courses from A&I. And we

37:32.658 --> 37:45.838
started, all of us, I mean all of the young teachers 
in those days, we started taking courses because

37:32.658 --> 37:45.838
in the first place, my father wouldn't dream of my 
going to school. Away from home. I went to Austin

37:51.347 --> 37:56.995
for six weeks to the University of Texas But daddy 
took me and we stayed in what was called Newman

37:57.464 --> 38:05.814
Hole, run by nuns. But father thought that being 
run by nuns, we would be in at 8 o'clock and that we

38:06.715 --> 38:18.589
would be supervised by nuns. He didn't realize 
that we were free to do whatever we wanted to. Of

38:22.354 --> 38:26.779
course, I mean, I knew better and I knew exactly how 
to behave. thanks to, I'm proud to say that he

38:27.198 --> 38:31.564
instilled that in us. Then, later on, I kept on 
taking courses here in Laredo. And then, since

38:39.495 --> 38:51.552
Kingsville was not far, I used to take courses by 
going on Saturdays, and by attending school

38:39.495 --> 38:51.552
during the summer months. And I stayed in the city 
court at home, which was run by the Sisters of

38:52.342 --> 38:57.827
Mercy. So the only way that Daddy would have 
consented to my going off to school for a whole one

38:59.168 --> 39:12.461
or two years would have been if I would have been in a 
convict with high walls. Broken glass on top? Yes,

39:15.183 --> 39:17.626
yes, yes. Bless his heart. Well, how many years did 
you teach before you got married? About four. Four

39:24.558 --> 39:24.999
years. And what did you teach? I always taught the 
elementary grades. My last years, I was head

39:31.008 --> 39:34.473
teacher. Then, instead of being assistant 
principal, you were a head teacher. And Mrs.

39:40.022 --> 39:44.308
Smith, I didn't teach in this particular school 
across the street. I taught in another one

39:44.328 --> 39:46.952
that's... Oh, well, more or less going towards 
Zapata. What's called now Dykes School, but it was

39:53.539 --> 39:56.323
Montrose. And I was head teacher there for several 
years. And then I was made, we had a new principal,

40:00.288 --> 40:04.775
Mr. Barrow. And I was made assistant principal. 
And then Mr. Barrow passed away and I was made

40:07.479 --> 40:10.203
principal. So I was a principal for Montrose 
School for several years. And I retired when I was

40:14.248 --> 40:17.513
not Not old, I mean, not old enough to get all the 
benefits. But I thought, well, I've helped my

40:23.201 --> 40:29.028
husband enough, and I want to be home and enjoy 
life. And they used to say, but look, now that

40:29.829 --> 40:36.157
you're a principal, you're going to retire. Yes, I 
made up my mind. I'm going to retire, and that's it.

40:42.805 --> 40:48.192
Would you believe that my first retirement check 
was $79?

40:51.479 --> 40:54.724
I'm still getting it because they're different. 
You can choose one, two, or three, and I can't

40:55.825 --> 40:59.390
remember what number. I think one, you get the 
whole bulk. Number two is something else. I chose

41:04.257 --> 41:09.986
the third,

41:04.257 --> 41:09.986
whatever you call it. And it has been raised. Now I 
get $129.

41:17.450 --> 41:20.855
If you'd taught until you were 65 or something. 
Until I was 60. If I would have taught until I was 60,

41:22.177 --> 41:28.546
I would have made a much, much, much higher salary. 
I mean, I would have received a much higher

41:28.566 --> 41:34.495
retirement check. But I don't regret it. I really 
don't. Because in the first place, my husband

41:36.678 --> 41:40.965
doesn't need it. And I don't feel like I have 
accomplished more by being home. than by

41:47.065 --> 41:48.166
teaching. I enjoyed my years of teaching. I really 
did. And I'm proud to say that my children still

41:51.870 --> 41:54.974
remember me.

41:58.217 --> 42:04.925
Children's mothers still remember me, the 
teachers that were with me when I was a principal.

42:05.445 --> 42:15.857
Whenever they see me, they say, we'll never have 
another principal like you, and things like that,

42:05.445 --> 42:15.857
which do make you feel proud of the fact that you 
retired before you got too cranky. Well, did you

42:18.402 --> 42:24.211
stop teaching at all when you were having your 
children? Except,

42:24.331 --> 42:28.858
let me see. When Renato Jr. was born, I didn't teach 
the first semester because he was born in

42:30.460 --> 42:37.511
November. This was your oldest son. My oldest son. 
Then when Javier was born, I taught all the year,

42:40.171 --> 42:44.477
the whole year. And then when my baby was born, my 
young one was born, I had two miscarriages during

42:44.497 --> 42:52.266
that time. And so the doctor and my husband said, 
no, you're not going to teach. But I felt like I

42:57.253 --> 43:05.443
wanted to teach because I had put so many years that 
I wanted to get the benefits that were due to me.

43:05.463 --> 43:06.565
That's the reason I taught. I've always put it this 
way. At first, I taught because I had to and because

43:09.483 --> 43:13.409
I liked it. First because I liked it and then 
because I had to. Then I taught because my husband

43:17.476 --> 43:30.917
needed, I wanted to help him so that we would really 
be able to get to where we are now. But the last years

43:31.606 --> 43:37.353
that I taught, I taught because I considered that I 
should. I was entitled to a little benefit for all

43:37.373 --> 43:44.402
the years that I had put into the profession. And my 
husband used to say every time, he said, please,

43:44.422 --> 43:59.381
honey, I don't want you to come home and be tearful 
because this little boy didn't have shoes and the

43:44.422 --> 43:59.381
other child needed a haircut and things like that. 
I said, now look. If I sell buttons and lace and

44:01.643 --> 44:16.199
thread, in other words, if I go to work as a clerk, 
then I promise you that I will never come home

44:01.643 --> 44:16.199
talking about my work. But as long as it's children 
that I'm dealing with, I'm going to do it with all my

44:16.600 --> 44:23.367
heart. And I'm going to give them everything that I 
can. There's really no other way. Oh, no.

44:29.925 --> 44:31.607
Otherwise, you're not a teacher. No, you have to be 
calling. You have to have a calling for it. I

44:38.717 --> 44:46.328
baptized children that were 9 and 10 years old, 
because they had never been baptized. I took

44:47.490 --> 44:49.453
children to the barber shop because the mother had 
made a promise that if he got well, they would let

44:49.788 --> 44:59.282
his hair grow, which now would be very, very 
popular. Oh, yes, a promessa. Yes, yes, things

45:02.086 --> 45:04.370
like that. Oh, my, that's interesting. And they 
would come to me, the mothers would come to me, and

45:08.235 --> 45:13.483
my husband didn't bring any money. They cut off the 
gas and they cut off the water. And I remember a

45:16.912 --> 45:25.064
butcher at ATV one time I went and I helped the 
family as I could. And he told me, Ms. Zapata, I want

45:25.124 --> 45:28.649
to ask a favor of you. I don't want you to interfere 
with my family. I said, oh, no. Never will I

45:32.435 --> 45:34.237
interfere with your family. But if your family, if 
your children are hungry, I am going to interfere.

45:39.245 --> 45:42.209
And nobody in this world is going to keep me from 
doing it. Neither you nor I.

